    <div class="putting-it-together">
        <h2>Putting It All Together</h2>
        <div class="summary">
            <h4>The Complete Migration Picture</h4>
            <p>When you work with .NET and databases, migrations handle the synchronization:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>You write C# code</strong> - Define what your data should look like</li>
                <li><strong>Migrations translate</strong> - Convert your C# changes to SQL commands</li>
                <li><strong>Database updates</strong> - Apply the changes safely</li>
                <li><strong>History tracked</strong> - Every change is recorded in migration files</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Your job is simple:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Change your C# classes when needed</li>
                <li>Run <code>Add-Migration</code> with a good name</li>
                <li>Run <code>Update-Database</code> to apply changes</li>
                <li>Test that everything still works</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The framework does the complex database work. You just write C# and run two commands!</p>
        </div>
    </div>


